AB  - BACKGROUND: In this post-hoc analysis, we determined the influence of
      single nucleotide polymorphisms in host candidate immune genes on the
      outcome of drug resistant malaria in Cameroon. METHODS: Human DNA from 760
      patients from a previous clinical trial was subjected to mass
      spectrometry-based single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) genotyping. Allele
      frequencies of candidate immune genes were calculated for 62 SNPs on 17
      human chromosomes for their possible involvement in clearance of
      drug-resistant parasites with the triple mutations of pfcrt76T, pfmdr86Y,
      and pfmdr1246Y (TY) and pfdhfr51I, pfdhfr59R, pfdhfr108N, and pfdhps437G
      (IRNG) which were determined by dotblot or PCR-restriction analysis.
      Differences in SNP frequencies and association analysis were carried out
      by comparing Chi-square odds ratios (ORs) and stratified by Mantel-Haenzel
      statistics. An adjusted P value (OR) 39°C for 48 hours) [IL-22, P = 0·01,
      OR = 1·5, 95% CI (OR): 1·8-2·1] and also in high frequency among the
      Fulani participants [P = 0·006, OR = 1·83, 95% CI (OR): 1·11-3·08)]. The
      CD36-1264 null allele was completely absent in the northern population.
      CONCLUSION: Independent association of SNPs in IL22 and IL-4 with
      clearance of amodiaquine- and sulphadoxine/pyrimethamine-resistant
      parasites did not reach statistical significance, but may suggest that not
      all drug-resistant mutants are adversely affected by the same
      immune-mediated mechanisms of clearance.
