AB  - Malaria is still one of the major killer parasitic diseases in tropical
      settings, posing a public health threat. The development of antimalarial
      drug resistance is reversing the gains made in attempts to control the
      disease. The parasite leads a complex life cycle that has adapted to
      outwit almost all known antimalarial drugs to date, including the first
      line of treatment, artesunate. There is a high unmet need to develop new
      strategies and identify novel therapeutics to reverse antimalarial drug
      resistance development. Among the strategies, here we focus and discuss
      the merits of the development of antimalarials targeting the Heat shock
      protein 90 (Hsp90) due to the central role it plays in protein quality
      control.
